  "method": "We propose Pessimistic Support-Weighted Advantage Cloning (PSWAC), a fully offline algorithm that learns only from logs while avoiding extrapolation. First, fit a behavior model π_b(a|s) and a support score σ(s,a) over the dataset D. σ combines (i) the behavior likelihood (or a density ratio upper bound) and, when logs come from multiple past policies, (ii) context-dependent propensities learned by harvesting implicit interventions across rankers/deployments to estimate exposure of (s,a). We then define a binary support mask M(s,a)=1[σ(s,a)≥τ] and a soft penalty ρ(s,a)=1−σ(s,a) for actions with weak support. In parallel, train an ensemble of Q-critics with bootstrap resampling to obtain both value estimates and epistemic uncertainty u(s,a) via ensemble variance.\n\nFor value learning, use a pessimistic Bellman objective. The target for each transition is y=r+γ·min_k Q_k^LCB(s',a'), where a' is sampled from a support-respecting proposal (e.g., π_b masked by M) and Q^LCB(s,a)=Q(s,a)−λ·u(s,a)−τ_p·ρ(s,a) serves as a lower confidence bound. Additionally, add a conservative regularizer that explicitly penalizes large Q on low-support actions by sampling counterfactual actions from a proposal that emphasizes ρ(s,a). To robustify against outliers and mislabeled returns common in logs, fit each critic with a heavy‑tailed regression loss (e.g., Student’s t) rather than squared error, which downweights sporadic high‑TD‑error samples that would otherwise inflate Q on unsupported actions.\n\nFor policy learning, avoid direct Q‑maximization and instead perform support‑weighted advantage cloning. Compute LCB advantages A_LCB(s,a)=Q^LCB(s,a)−E_{a'~π_b}[Q^LCB(s,a')]. Train π by maximizing E_{(s,a)~D}[ M(s,a)·exp(β·A_LCB(s,a))·log π(a|s) ] subject to a small KL trust region to π_b. This yields a closed‑form target π*(a|s) ∝ M(s,a)·π_b(a|s)·exp(β·A_LCB(s,a)) that stays within support while upweighting advantageous deviations. Practically, we instantiate this either as (i) weighted behavior cloning with dynamic weights w(s,a)=M·exp(β·A_LCB), or (ii) a step‑wise preference loss on pairs (a+,a−) drawn from the same state where a+ has higher A_LCB—an offline objective that is theoretically equivalent to an on‑policy policy‑gradient under a shaped reward, ensuring stable improvement without importance sampling.\n\nFor model selection and safety, perform conservative offline evaluation with a doubly robust estimator that blends the learned propensity model and the LCB critics. When multiple loggers exist, use interventional sets to reduce bias in propensity learning and calibrate uncertainty; accept a new policy only if its LCB‑DR estimate exceeds the baseline by a preset margin. If the setting contains many related tasks (e.g., user‑personalized bandits or contextual subtasks), share structure across tasks via a hierarchical prior over critic parameters to tighten LCBs, enabling stronger yet safe improvements from limited per‑task data.",
  "rationale": "The method addresses distribution mismatch by explicitly constraining optimization to the logged support (mask M and penalty ρ) and by applying pessimism through lower confidence bounds that subtract both uncertainty and low‑support penalties from Q. This prevents the policy from relying on extrapolated values for actions rarely or never seen in the logs. Using an ensemble and a heavy‑tailed critic loss further stabilizes value estimation under dataset noise.\n\nInstead of brittle Q‑maximization, advantage‑weighted cloning steers the policy toward higher‑value actions while remaining close to π_b and strictly within support, which is known to reduce extrapolation. Casting the policy update as a step‑wise preference objective whose gradient matches an on‑policy policy gradient under a shaped reward provides a principled offline improvement mechanism without high‑variance importance sampling. Finally, learning context‑dependent propensities from implicit interventions and employing a conservative doubly‑robust OPE enables safe selection of improved policies from logs alone.",
