  "method": "Support-Constrained, Uncertainty-Guided Offline RL (SCU-ORL)\n\n1) Learn a calibrated behavior model and a fast uncertainty/support estimator from logs. Fit an expressive conditional policy β(a|s) on the dataset with maximum likelihood; for high-dimensional actions, parameterize β as a structured density (e.g., a Bayesian-network–factorized normalizing flow) so we can sample and evaluate per-dimension likelihoods efficiently. In parallel, learn a deterministic uncertainty head u(s,a) by embedding (s,a) into a prototype-based latent space and training for distinction maximization; treat low prototype affinity as high uncertainty. Combine both into a support score σ(s,a) = sigmoid(c1 · log β(a|s) − c2 · u(s,a)), which serves as a soft mask indicating how much an action is in-distribution at state s.\n\n2) Train a pessimistic, in-sample critic without max over unseen actions. Learn Qθ with TD on logged state–action pairs using the target y = r + γ Vϕ(s′). Estimate Vϕ(s) by expectile regression over in-dataset actions only: fit V to the τ-expectile of Q(s,·) using samples a ~ β(·|s) reweighted by σ(s,a), avoiding extrapolation to unsupported actions. Add a conservative penalty that pushes down Q on actions away from the behavior support: Lconsv = η · (E_{a~p_wide(·|s)}[Qθ(s,a)] − E_{a~β(·|s)}[Qθ(s,a)]), where p_wide is a broad proposal around β (e.g., behavior noise or a temperature-raised sampler). Weight the penalty by state novelty U(s) = Ea[1 − σ(s,a)] so pessimism increases where support is weak. This yields stable, pessimistic values estimated strictly on in-sample (or near-support) actions.\n\n3) Improve the policy with support-gated advantage-weighted cloning under a per-state trust region. Compute advantages A(s,a) = Qθ(s,a) − Vϕ(s). Train πψ(a|s) by maximizing E_{(s,a)~D}[ w(s,a) · log πψ(a|s) ] with w(s,a) = clip(exp(A/λ), wmax) · σ(s,a), so only advantageous, in-support actions get amplified. Simultaneously keep π close to β via a per-state KL constraint DKL(π||β) ≤ ε enforced by a Lagrange multiplier α: minimize E_s[ α (DKL(π||β) − ε) ] alongside the cloning objective. Update α online to meet the target ε. For discrete actions, optionally refine selection locally by re-ranking only the top-k actions sampled from β using Qθ with a few adjacent comparisons, keeping inference cheap and within support.\n\n4) Make conservatism and trust adapt to uncertainty during training and deployment. Update the pessimism coefficient η and the KL multiplier α with an uncertainty-guided EMA schedule: increase them when U(s) is high and relax them when U(s) is low, smoothing over batches to avoid oscillations. Use bootstrapped target networks and cross-fitting to reduce overestimation. At deployment, form a novelty-adaptive mixture πdeploy(a|s) = (1 − ρ(s)) πψ(a|s) + ρ(s) β(a|s), where ρ(s) = clip(Ea[1 − σ(s,a)], 0, ρmax), to fall back to logged behavior in unfamiliar regions while exploiting learned advantages in well-supported regions.",
  "rationale": "The core failure mode in offline RL is extrapolation: max operators and policy improvement over unseen actions inflate Q on out-of-distribution actions, leading to brittle policies. This method removes the need to evaluate or optimize over unsupported actions by (i) learning values purely from in-sample actions via expectile value regression, (ii) regularizing Q pessimistically on actions outside the behavior support, and (iii) constraining policy improvement to advantage-weighted cloning inside the learned support while enforcing a per-state KL trust region to the behavior.\n\nA fast, deterministic uncertainty estimate and an explicit behavior density together provide a principled support score that gates both critic and actor updates and drives adaptive regularization. The result is a strong policy extracted from logs alone that exploits advantages where the data are reliable, stays close to the behavior where they are not, and avoids extrapolation errors without requiring any online interaction.",
